  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_831510343" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/831510343" />
    <a title="Suzanne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3695758-suzanne"><img alt="Suzanne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1369500256p2/3695758.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/831510343?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Suzanne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Suzanne" href="/user/show/3695758-suzanne">Suzanne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">anyone interested in the 1920s</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3695758-suzanne?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3695758-suzanne?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer831510343" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12471749960917806289">Charles Lindbergh’s solo transatlantic flight from Long Island to Paris launches this book and author Bill Bryson describes the insane levels of global celebrity and adoration Lindbergh achieved by winning the distinction of being the first person to cross a major ocean by air. It was a little like Beatlemania, only with one guy and no music. <br/><br/><i>One Summer: America, 1927 </i> is a social history of the United States in the year 1927, organized around the famous personalities of the day and their accomp</span>
  <span id="freeText12471749960917806289" style="display:none">Charles Lindbergh’s solo transatlantic flight from Long Island to Paris launches this book and author Bill Bryson describes the insane levels of global celebrity and adoration Lindbergh achieved by winning the distinction of being the first person to cross a major ocean by air. It was a little like Beatlemania, only with one guy and no music. <br /><br /><i>One Summer: America, 1927 </i> is a social history of the United States in the year 1927, organized around the famous personalities of the day and their accomplishments that year, with plenty of back-story for context and entertainment. Bryson’s amusing and often witty writing style was a bonus. <br /><br />Babe Ruth, who was raised in a group home where his father dumped him at age 7, is profiled as a lusty, beloved, and extraordinarily talented athlete. The history and rise of baseball as the great American pastime is chronicled, along with the invention of the hot dog and career highlights of the other major league baseball players of that era such as Ty Cobb and Lou Gehric. There are also quite a lot of stories about the popular sport of boxing and Jack Dempsey and other major fighters. And everybody got to listen to the events no matter where they were because of this new-fangled thing called radio. It was all the rage. While the sports scores and statistics were a bit much for me, I admit I got a little misty at the end of Gehric’s career. <br /><br />There was also some history about the early development of television, who invented it and who took all the credit for inventing it. Poor Philo Farnsworth totally got screwed. <br /><br />Bryson writes of the staid and somber President Calvin Coolidge; his predecessor, the more genial but scandal-plagued Warren Harding; the genesis of Herbert Hoover’s career; and the resurgence of the Klu Klux Klan, along with the emergence of the ‘science’ of eugenics to justify rising waves of bigotry. Major natural disasters, like floods along the Mississippi, plagued the land, as well as man-made ones such as Prohibition, the stupidest government experiment of all time. It worked out well for a lot of criminals though. Al Capone did quite well for himself in this climate and the corruption in Chicago that enabled him and others like him to thrive was so extreme as to be almost comical. I learned that the person who came up with the strategy to finally catch Capone on charges that would stick, after all else had failed, was a woman, Mabel Walker Willebrandt, then U.S. Assistant Attorney General. <br /><br />I also learned that Henry Ford was a very strange man. Another strange set of billionaires, back when a billion was actually worth something, were the inseparable brothers Oris and Mantis Swearingen whose leveraged buyouts in real estate and railroads made them on paper, very , very wealthy -- until the crash of 1929, after which they died with about $6,000 between them. There is back-story about back room dealings between high level financiers that set up the conditions for the Crash of 1929 and the Great Depression. <br /><br />Among other topics the book covers are the rise of radical labor movement between the wars and the controversial trials and executions of the accused radicals Sacco and Vancetti. This gives Bryson an opportunity to bring in the development of electrocution as a means of dispatching criminals convicted of capital crimes and profile the man who came to be New York State’s official executioner. This was one Robert Elliot, who had been promoted from the position of electrician, who is supposed to have perfected the technique of utilizing just the right amount of current to fry people both lethally and humanely. 			<br /><br />Of course the movie business was jumping in 1927, with 100 million tickets sold every week. Huge and elaborate theaters were built in all major cities, but both the exhibition and productions side of the business were struggling. The economics of the movie business were such that, after the end of block booking, the industry was both ‘hugely successful and gravely imperiled at the same time.’ 1927 was the year of ‘Wings,’ the first-ever Best Picture winner, called here ‘one of the most intelligent, moving and thrilling motion pictures ever made’; it was directed by a WWI combat pilot vet, with more realistic air-combat sequences than had ever been seen before. It was also the year of Al Jolson’s ‘The Jazz Singer’ that changed movies forever. It was the zenith of Clara Bow’s career, a charismatic actress who was both hardworking (35 movies in five years) and ‘dazzlingly promiscuous’ (no exact count given). <br /><br /><i>One Summer: America, 1927</i> was educational and entertaining. Highly recommended to anyone interested in the era. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12471749960917806289" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


